metadata.name: Maru #23
metadata.description:
Maru means “circle” in Japanese, it also represents many other things like integrity, infinity and the universe. The art generated through my exploration with circles felt like it needed this name.

Best viewed in full screen, Press s in live mode for a 1414x2000 download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje Oktober 2022

metadata.name: looking through a glass #34
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: The Samsara-Verse #44
metadata.description:
Samsara is the endless Wheel of Life, where uncountable numbers of souls ceaselessly wander through its 6 realms - Deva-gati (abode of the gods), Asura-gati (demi-gods), Preta-gati (hungry ghosts), Naraka-gati (Hell), Tiryagyoni-gati (animals), Manusya-gati (the human realm).
 
These realms are interleaved with manifold planes of existence separated by the thinnest of veils.
And yet - these hives of endless activity are but a small fraction of the totality of the metaverse, as multitudes of unformed universes, as yet mere sketches, await their blooming.

This artwork consists of both a visual aspect and a sonic representation echoing the voices of the denizens of the various planes of the Samsara-Verse.

Once the piece has finished drawing, click or press "m" to unmute the soundtrack.
Press "s" to save the image as a ".png" file (4800x3600 pixels).

Collaborative work by Geoffrey Crayon - art design and coding - and Cylonix (JJClark) - sound design. The audio samples used (in addition to generative drones) are from Loopology and Splice.

metadata.description: Contemporary visual art composition representing an urban and industrial landscape. Art created in p5js.

metadata.name: Unstable Anticipation #134
metadata.description:
Minimal poster prints of blocks in motion.

Varying block arrangements fall from the canvas's top and interact with pegs near the bottom. After the animation completes, the scene is redrawn with a halftone pattern.

Matter JS is used to calculate the physics.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px

Features
* The length of the simulation
* Number, size, and position of the pegs
* Halftone grid size
* Varying amount of roughness for distorted halftone shapes
* Shape arrangement and composition
* 60/40% Color or monochrome

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #12
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution
